Linux architecture is a layered system designed for stability and security, separating user applications from physical hardware. It consists primarily of the User Space (applications/shell) and Kernel Space (core OS). The monolithic kernel directly manages hardware, memory, and processes, acting as the bridge for all system operations.


Core Layers of Linux Architecture
Hardware Layer: Physical components, including the CPU, RAM, and hard drives.
Kernel: The heart of the OS, responsible for process management, memory management, file systems, and device drivers. It runs in privileged mode.
System Call Interface (SCI): A layer that allows user-space applications to request services from the kernel.
System Libraries (glibc): Provide functions that apps use to make system calls without knowing the complex kernel interface.
Shell/User Space: The topmost layer where user applications, daemons, and terminal interfaces exist, running with restricted access to hardware for security.

Key Components and Functionality
Monolithic Kernel: The Linux kernel runs all its core functions—drivers, file system, memory management—in a single, privileged space.
User Space vs. Kernel Space: Memory is separated to prevent user applications from crashing the entire system, increasing reliability.
System Calls: When a program (e.g., a text editor) needs to interact with hardware (e.g., save a file), it issues a system call to the kernel, which then communicates with the hardware controller.
Shell: A command-line interpreter that lets users interact with the OS by sending commands to the kernel.

